\ul\b\i\fs24 6. Main Config file "f2_res.ini"\par
\par
\ulnone\b0\i0\fs20 This is where your current screen resolution and other settings are stored. Many of the below setting can be adjusted using the "f2_res_Config.exe" or the in-game menu.\par
The "f2_res.ini" file is divided into nine sections MAIN, EFFECTS, HI_RES_PANEL, MOVIES, MAPS, IFACE, MAINMENU, STATIC_SCREENS and OTHER_SETTINGS.\par
\i\fs18 Note: If using Windows Vista/7/8 and above, the active ini may not be the one located in your install directory. To easily find and edit your ini manually, click the "Manually Edit Config" button in the Hi-res Patch f2_res_Config.exe program. See \b User Account Control Compatibility (UAC_AWARE=1) \b0 below for more info\b .\fs20\par
\b0\par
\i0\par
\par
\ul\b\i MAIN\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\par
\b User Account Control Compatibility (UAC_AWARE=1)\par
\b0 Affects Windows Vista/7/8 and above. This setting is only read from the f2_res.ini found in your games install directory. It allows hi-res patch settings to be changed without admin privileges if installed in the "Program Files" directory. When enabled the f2_res.ini is recreated in your user roaming app data folder. For Vista this is usually "C:\\Documents and Settings\\'your user name'\\Application Data\\Fallout2". For Windows 7/8 this is usually "C:\\Users\\'your user name'\\AppData\\Roaming\\Fallout2".\par
Under this folder your f2_res.ini will be located in another folder which is named with a hash code based on the path of your games install directory. This was done to allow multiple installs of fallout2 to have different settings.\par
To easily find and edit your ini manually, click the "Manually Edit Config" button in the Hi-res Patch f2_res_Config.exe program.\par
\par
\b Graphics Mode (GRAPHICS_MODE=1)\par
\b0 There are three graphic modes:\par
GRAPHICS_MODE=0 "Basic mode" Only the fullscreen resolution can be adjusted using this mode, other display settings have no effect. Basic mode is required to use Sfall's graphic modes.\par
GRAPHICS_MODE=1 "Direct Draw 7 mode" Display output rendered using Direct Draw 7.\par
GRAPHICS_MODE=2 "DirectX 9 mode" Display output rendered using DirectX 9.\par
\par
\b 2X Scaling (SCALE_2X=0)\par
\b0 Set to 1 to enable scaling the game to twice the size. May come in handy for large displays. It requires a screen resolution 1280x960 or greater. Windowed mode will require a little more space for the window border.\b\par
\par
Fullscreen Dimensions (SCR_WIDTH = & SCR_HEIGHT =)\par
\b0 Set your custom fullscreen resolution here.\b\par
\b0\par
\b Fullscreen Colours (COLOUR_BITS = 8)\b0\par
Can be set to 8 for 8bit colour (default), 16 for 16bit colour or 32 for 32bit colour output.\par
\b\par
Fullscreen Refresh Rate (REFRESH_RATE=0)\b0\par
Set to 0, the refresh rate is set by the driver. Otherwise set your fullscreen refresh rate here.\par
\b\par
Enable\\Disable Window Mode (WINDOWED=1)\b0\par
Set to 1 to play the game in a resizable window.\par
\b\par
Fullscreen Window Mode (WINDOWED_FULLSCREEN=0)\b0\par
When enabled and \b WINDOWED=1\b0 . Will start fallout in a borderless fullscreen top level window, with resolution and colour settings matching those of your desktop.\par
\b\par
Window Mode Data (WIN_DATA=0)\b0\par
This setting is a block of data relating to window size and position and should not be modified here.\par
\b\par
Hi-res Dat file path (f2_res_dat = f2_res.dat)\b0\par
Sets the location of the Dat file which holds graphic and text resources for the Screen Settings Window as well as map edge data for all original Fallout2 maps.\par
\b\par
Hi-res Dat patch folder path (f2_res_patches=data\\)\b0\par
Sets the location of the patch folder for the Hi-res Dat file.\par
\b\par
\par
\ul\i INPUT\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\b\par
Alternative Mouse Input (ALT_MOUSE_INPUT=0)\b0\par
Set ALT_MOUSE_INPUT=1 to enable the hi-res patches alternative mouse input, which uses windows messages instead of DirectInput. This may help those getting "Failure initializing input devices" errors on game start. It also has extra options for the mouse middle button and scroll wheel.\par
\b\par
Fix for "NOT RESPONDING" error in Windowed Mode (EXTRA_WIN_MSG_CHECKS=0)\b0\par
When enabled, adds extra windows message checks to several loops during combat and in fade effects. This setting is always enabled if ALT_MOUSE_INPUT=1.\par
\ul\i\fs18 Note\ulnone : This error has only been seen in Fallout1, so is disabled by default for Fallout2.\i0\fs20\par
\b\par
Mouse Wheel Default Focus (SCROLLWHEEL_FOCUS_PRIMARY_MENU=1)\b0\par
When enabled and accessing the inventory, barter, loot screens etc.  Mouse wheel control will default to the Player Character's item list unless the cursor is hovering over another list.\par
\b\par
\par
\ul\i EFFECTS\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\par
\b Black and White TV Mode (IS_GRAY_SCALE=0)\b0\par
Play the game without colour. This was Pixote's wacky idea, to give the game that 1950's feel. To enable set to 1.\par
\par
\b\par
\ul\i HI_RES_PANEL\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\par
\b Display List Descending/Ascending (DISPLAY_LIST_DESCENDING = 1)\b0\par
Here you can set the order of the resolution list in the Screen Settings Window. Descending order by default.\par
\par
\par
\ul\b\i MOVIES\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\par
\b Movie Size (MOVIE_SIZE = 1)\b0\par
Here you can set how the movies are displayed.\par
If set to 0, Movie will display at its original size.\par
If set to 1, Movie will stretch to fit the screen while maintaining its aspect ratio.\par
If set to 2, Movie will stretch to fill the screen.\par
\par
\par
\ul\b\i MAPS\par
\ulnone\i0\par
Enable\\Disable Edge Clipping (EDGE_CLIPPING_ON=1)\par
\b0 Set to 1 (On by default). This setting clips the area beyond scroll edges when the screen resolution is greater than the map being viewed. Set to 0 to disable. \par
\b\par
Ignore Map Edges (IGNORE_MAP_EDGES = 0)\par
\b0 Set to 0 (Off by default). If set to 1(On) this setting ignores the map edges preventing you scrolling outside the playable area of a map. \par
\par
\b Ignore Player Scroll Limits (IGNORE_PLAYER_SCROLL_LIMITS= 0)\par
\b0 Set to 0 (Off by default). If set to 1(On) this setting ignores the scroll limits from the player set below by the variables SCROLL_DIST_X and SCROLL_DIST_Y.\par
\par
\b Player Scroll Distance (SCROLL_DIST_X & SCROLL_DIST_Y)\b0\par
By default the scroll distance from the player is set to the\i  \ul screen edge + 1 tile\ulnone  \i0 in both directions. Setting a distance less than the screen edge can cause problems.\par
\par
\b Path Finding Range  (NumPathNodes = 1)\b0\par
Extends the path finding range by increasing the number of nodes used for plotting the path. The number of nodes equals the value of "NumPathNodes" multiplied by 2000. e.g. 1=2000(original), 2=4000, 3=6000 ..etc. up to 20=40000(max).\par
Each block of 2000 nodes requires an additional 160000 bytes (156.25 KB) of memory, with the maximum of 40000 nodes requiring 3200000 bytes (3125 KB).\par
\par
\b Enable\\Disable Fog Of War (FOG_OF_WAR=0)\par
\b0 Set to 1 to enable the Fog Of War Mod. This option darkens scenery, walls and floor tiles on the area of a map not yet seen by the Player Character. It completely hide all other objects until discovery, with NPCs only visible when in line of sight of the Player Character. It also prevents the mouse "look at" function from seeing undiscovered stuff.\par
This option is best enabled before entering a map for the first time as it uses the object discovery flags already built into the game for displaying stuff on the local map viewer. Enabling this after entering a map will look weird, as discovered objects will be visible while the floor tiles below them will still appear darkened.\par
\par
\b Adjust the Fog Of War light level (FOG_OF_WAR=4)\par
\b0 Adjust how dark the fog appears. Light level ranges between 1-10 with 1 being the darkest. Setting this to 0 will display everything at normal light level and allow undiscovered scenery and walls to respond to the mouse "look at" function. All other objects will remain invisible until discovered by the Player Character.\par
\par
\ul\b\i IFACE\par
\ulnone\b0\i0\par
\b Height of the Viewable Map Area (IFACE_BAR_MODE = 0)\b0\par
By default the Viewable Map Area will sit above the Interface-Bar. Setting to 1 will lower the bottom of the Viewable Area to the bottom of the screen. Side bar graphics will be disabled in this mode.\par
\par
\b Interface-Bar Side-Bar Graphics Art (IFACE_BAR_SIDE_ART = 2)\par
\b0 Sets which optional art is used to fill the spaces either side of the Interface-bar.\par
Options are:\par
Set to 2 (default) for the Leather Pipboy Belt art created by me.\par
